0DBA61B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Media System, Political Context and Informed Citizenship: A Comparative Study</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H025561/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The overall objective of this study is to investigate what influences informed citizenship. It is based on a study of eight nations, in four continents, and focuses on the organisation of the media, what is reported, and on differences of political culture and context.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This study investigates whether market-driven media give greater prominence to celebrity and entertainment news than to politics compared with public service media. It will also investigate whether national differences in what is reported are related to what is known. For example, are Americans expert in celebrity news, Norwegians well versed in international news, and the Japanese especially informed about domestic politics?&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This investigation will also explore whether differences between societies&amp;nbsp;- for instance, in the degree of political partisanship, peoples? perception of whether government is effective, relative investment in education, and degree of economic inequality&amp;nbsp;- affect the level of news consumption, and whether this in turn influences knowledge of public affairs.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Co-funded by the ERSRC, and seven other agencies ranging from the Japanese Research Council to Sky Italia, the study is based on a quantitative study of news and representative national surveys.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78968</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>News media : windows on the world?</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:id>76035C97-D45D-46C8-A316-7D23CAB5507C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Paper presented on November 15th 2011 at the Psychology Programme Seminar Series at Canterbury Christ Church University</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The internet : prophecy and reality</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>93E19263-2493-4FD3-A7D1-2B59CF294116</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This public presentation will examine what experts have said would happen as a result of the internet,

and what has actually happened. While the internet has effected some significant changes, the

transformations that were predicted have not occurred. The internet has not, as confidently claimed by

many commentators:

? provided a geyser of prosperity;

? promoted global understanding;

? empowered the powerless;

? caused the fall of dictatorships, or

? generated a renaissance of journalism.

Indeed many forecasts have been unfulfilled. Why, then, has internet prophecy so often departed from

